        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-01T22:31:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why is this the right error message for this case?  The only way I can see for cmd-\u003efenceSync to be null is if triggerWait is called with a NULL fenceSync.  Nothing modifies the funceSync field to NULL to indicate that the signal has happened, which I thought might be what you were talking about.\n\nPerhaps triggerWait should assert that the fenceSync argument is non-null, so we could justify making a similar assertion here, rather than just a DPRINT.\n\nAFAICT, eglClientWaitSyncKHR does not allow the caller to know that the fence was already signaled when it was called.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 243,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 245,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "348b0ae2_c06b1eed",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/SyncThread.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 245,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-02T15:16:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "cmd-\u003efenceSync is not a raw OpenGL / EGL sync object; it\u0027s a FenceSyncInfo object that is introduced in one of this patch\u0027s dependencies (https://android-review.googlesource.com/248563).\n\nWe track the actually-signaled status of any cmd-\u003efenceSync objects manually in https://android-review.googlesource.com/248563. It\u0027s possible for more than one thread to issue waits on the same OpenGL sync object created in the guest, and we want to know ASAP when the sync object is actually signaled, because we can avoid extra overhead of eglClientWaitSyncKHR calls.\n\nIn particular, we purposely set cmd-\u003efenceSync to NULL when we know that the original OpenGL sync object is already signaled. NULL signifies both signaled status and the fact that we don\u0027t want to use memory for tracking that sync object anymore.\n\nThe effect of already signaled fence objects is benign. The warning DPRINT is put here more out of curiosity, because according to my limited mental model, I usually don\u0027t expect the guest to pass us a OpenGL sync object on this code path while the guest also waits on it behind our backs in another guest rendering thread. But, it does happen, rarely, while playing Youtube videos or using the browser in general.",
      "parentUuid": "cf8db5b7_fa556054",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 243,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 245,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "54d23e19_843d6876",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/SyncThread.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 245,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-03T17:06:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If you\u0027re saying that the 248563 cl does the setting of cmd-\u003efenceSync to NULL, I don\u0027t see it doing that explicitly.  Are you perhaps saying that the return value of FenceSyncInfo::findNonSignaledSync from that CL is used as the input value to triggerWait, in some code not in either of these CLs?\n\nHaving raised the issue, I feel duty-bound to figure out how cmd-\u003efenceSync can be NULL in this test, and to verify that this means what you say :-).  I trust that it probably does, but if don\u0027t follow through, what\u0027s the purpose of code reviews :-)?",
      "parentUuid": "348b0ae2_c06b1eed",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 243,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 245,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "54d23e19_b05e267a",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/SyncThread.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 245,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-03T18:29:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It never hurts to verify, and in fact this issue you raised is especially on point :D\n\nI looked into it more, and it looks like although we are supposed to be calling setSignaled when a sync object is signaled, we are not doing that where it counts (either here, nor in yet another CL https://android-review.googlesource.com/223032 (sorry for being misleading there)).\n\nBut then, with all the other revisions and rebases that were going on, I think I totally dropped the setSignaled calls altogether.\n\nI also simplified FenceSyncInfo to just use the existence of FenceSync objects to represent signaled-ness. So that\u0027s quite bad, plus it also revealed a potential problem with FenceSyncInfo\u0027s collection of signaled/nonsignaled infos growing monotonically (also fixed).",
      "parentUuid": "54d23e19_843d6876",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 243,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 245,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cf8db5b7_5a7814d4",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/SyncThread.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 253,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-01T22:31:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is it the right thing to do the timeline increment below if the wait_result is not CONDITION_SATISFIED?  Is there a reasonable thing to do if the timeout expires?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 252,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 253,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "348b0ae2_202d2aaf",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/SyncThread.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 26
      },
      "lineNbr": 253,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-02T15:16:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here\u0027s what can happen on abnormal wait results:\n\n- normal operation: either the sync object is already signaled and we return immediately, or we wait till the object is signaled. both return EGL_CONDITION_SATISFIED_KHR.\n\n- timeout: the fence command we put in earlier in the OpenGL stream is not actually ever signaled, and we end up blocking in the above eglClientWaitSyncKHR call until our timeout runs out.\n\n- error: eglClientWaitSyncKHR errors out for some weird reason, but most likely having to do with the underlying EGL implementation not really supporting fence objects.\n\nTimeline increment is the correct response to all 3 cases because:\n\n- normal operation: we\u0027ve delayed enough to ensure the sync object is signaled, so increment the timeline.\n\n- timeout: we\u0027ve already timed out and made the guest thread that waits on that fence fd wait for at least as long as the timeout. Which, when using kDefaultTimeoutNsecs, is enough to trip error messages about fence fd\u0027s not being signaled in time. So we are properly emulating the bad behavior already; timeline increment after that isn\u0027t going to make things improperly better.\n\n- error: chances are, the underlying EGL implementation on the host doesn\u0027t actually support fence objects. In this case, we should fail safe: 1) It must be only very old or faulty graphics drivers / GPU\u0027s that don\u0027t support fence objects. 2) The consequences of signaling too early are generally, out of order frames and scrambled textures in some apps. But, not incrementing the timeline means that the app\u0027s rendering freezes. So, despite the faulty GPU driver, not incrementing is too heavyweight a response.",
      "parentUuid": "cf8db5b7_5a7814d4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 252,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 253,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "a097ec02a0d162aea702a3eb7fa63dbe397a2a80",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "54d23e19_e4d5540d",
